Modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load required packages and data.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(GGally)
load("movies.Rdata")

1. Data

The data contains details about 651 movies that were made between 1970 and 2014. The details involve theatrical release year, director, scores and ratings from critics and moviegoers, actors and actresses etc. There are a total of 32 variables which are given below.

names(movies)
##  [1] "title"            "title_type"       "genre"            "runtime"

1.1 Data collection and scope

The data has been randomly sampled from IMDB and rotten tomatoes. Therefore, the results are generalizable. The total number of 651 movies is good enough.

There is no random assignment because this is an observation data set. Therefore, No causal relationships can be inferred. Only associations and correlations can be inferred.

2. Research question

Is there an association between the variables run-time, critics’ score, critics’ rating, title type, genre, and whether a main actor or actress in the movie has won an academy award previously and the ‘Audience score’ of that movie.

Variables:
Response variable: audience_score
Explanatory variables: runtime, critics_score, critics_rating, title_type, genre, best_actor_win, best_actress_win

Rationale for the question: As an avid moviegoer, I am interested in finding out which factors determine the rating of a movie given by the audience. Movies with higher run-times might be boring to the viewers. Critical score and rating can bias the viewers’ assessment of the movie. Similar biases can be caused by big movie personalities such as previous Oscars winners. On the other hand, type of the movie can also determine the audience score. For example, people do not usually like documentaries. A similar argument can be made about the genre. Most people might prefer action movies.

3.1 Possible predictors of audience_score

Let us see whether there is an association between audience and critical scores.

  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm')

From a superficial look, it appears that there is an association between the two variables. Therefore, critics_score might be a predictor of audience_score.

Let us now investigate whether a similar trend can be seen for variables audience_score and runtime.

ggplot(data = mdata, aes(x = runtime, y = audience_score)) + 
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm')

It is appears that there is a negligible association between the two variables. It appears that runtime is not a good predictor of the variable audience_score. However, a better calculation based method would be required to come to a complete understanding.

Let us create a side by side boxplot between the audience_score and title_type variable.

ggplot(data = mdata, aes(x = title_type, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_boxplot(width=0.4)

It appears that documentaries have received high audience scores than feature films and TV movies. Whereas documentaries have the lowest IQR, TV movies have the highest. It might be possible that audience_score is associated with title_type variable.

Similar analyses for the possible relationships between the variables audience_score and best_actor_win and the variables audience_score and best_actress_win are given below.

ggplot(data = mdata, aes(x = best_actor_win, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_boxplot(width=0.4)

The ranges as well as the IQRs appear to be similar for both levels in the explanatory variable. Therefore, the distribution of audience_score variable appears to have no bearing on whether a main actor in a movie had previously won the Oscar award.

ggplot(data = mdata, aes(x = best_actress_win, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_boxplot(width=0.4)

The results of this is similar to that of the previous case. The ranges and IQRs are similar in both levels. It appears both best_actor_win and best_actress_win are not very important in predicting the audience_score. However, a better statistical analysis is required to reach a concrete answer.

Let us now check whether there is an association between the variables audience_score and critics_rating.

ggplot(data = mdata, aes(x = critics_rating, y = audience_score)) +
  geom_boxplot(width=0.4)

It appears that there is some correlation between the two variables i.e. movies with the critical rating “Certified Fresh” seems to have a median audience score above 75 and the IQR is the highest of three levels. The median audience rating seems to decrease with the critical score changing from “Certified Fresh” to “Rotten”.

The relationship between audience_score and the genre is examined below.

It is clear that genere introduces some variability to audience_score variable. The median of audience_score depends on the level of the genre variable. For instance, musicals and documentaries have median values higher than 75.

4. Modeling

4.1 Omitting some variables

Some explanatory variables in the data set might be co-linear i.e. have strong associations between themselves. Such variables would give rise to a biased model. For example, critics_score and critics_rating might be strongly associated because the latter is calculated based on the former. Therefore, critics_rating should be omitted from the model.

The relationship is given below.

ggplot(data = mdata, aes(x = critics_rating, y = critics_score)) + 
  geom_boxplot(width=0.4)

It is clear that “Certified Fresh” and “Fresh” ratings correspond to very high critics_score values (e.g. median equal to or above 75 in both cases). A “Rotten” rating is observed for low scored movies.

On the other hand, the variables such as director, actor1,2,3,4,5 are useless in the modeling. This is mainly because they have large number of levels and they do not make a statistical sense. Therefore, they were omitted from the model.

4.2 Full Model

The preliminary model is given below. The variables were given in the research question section. Variable names are the same used in the data frame.

\[\begin{align} \widehat{audience\_score} \sim & \ runtime \ + \ critics\_score \ +\ title\_type \ +\\ & \ best\_actor\_win \ +\ best\_actress\_win \ + \ genre \end{align}\]

4.3 Model selection method

Model selection method is backwards elimination based on the adjusted \(R^2\) value.

Rationale: Backwards elimination works based on a model containing a set of predictor variables. The aim is to remove variables that do not contribute to the prediction power of the model. As we already have a model, this method is suitable. Adjusted \(R^2\) is better than the P-value based method, because it is a more reliable indicator and it is not bound by an arbitrary cut off value like in the P-value based methods.

4.4 Model selection

The model is given below.

movmod = lm(audience_score ~ runtime + critics_score + title_type + best_actor_win +
              best_actress_win + genre, data = mdata)

Only the variables runtime, critics_score, and genre are statistically significant predictors of audience_score based on the t test of the full model. However, as we are using adjusted \(R^2\) for model selection, we shall continue with all the variables.

The highest adjusted \(R^2\) = 0.5228868 occurred when we dropped the variable title_type. Therefore, the new model is given below.

\[\begin{align} \widehat{audience\_score} \sim & \ runtime \ + \ critics\_score \ +\ best\_actor\_win \ +\ best\_actress\_win \ + \ genre \end{align}\]

Let us restart the process.

The details of the final model are given below.

## critics_score     0.45007    0.02175  20.697  < 2e-16 ***

## 
## Residual standard error: 13.97 on 637 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5323, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5235 
## F-statistic: 60.42 on 12 and 637 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The F-statistic is 60.42 and the associated probability is approximately 0. This implies that the model as whole is statistically significant and that at least one of the coefficients of the variables is significant. On the other hand, from the t values, it is apparent that all variables are statistically significant. The model is given as follows.

\[\begin{align} \widehat{audience\_score} = & \ 27.37 + 0.075 \times runtime \ + \ 0.45 \times critics\_score \ +\ 5.74 \times \text{genre:Art house} \ + \\ & \ 9.78 \times \text{genre:Musical} - 4.39 \times \text{genre:Mystery} -6.54 \times \text{genre:Sci-Fi} \ + \\ & \ 5.94 \times \text{genre:Animation} - 0.54 \times \text{genre:Comedy} + 9.45 \times \text{genre:Documentary} \ + \\ & \ 1.68 \times \text{genre:Drama} - 8.22 \times \text{genre:Horror} + 1.80 \times \text{genre:Other} \end{align}\]

The reference level of genre is “Action”.

4.5.1 Diagnostics

  1. Normality of residuals with mean 0
hist(movmod$residuals)

qqnorm(movmod$residuals); qqline(movmod$residuals)

mean(movmod$residuals)
## [1] 1.73882e-16

We can clearly see that the residuals are distributed nearly normally around an approximate mean of 0 \(( \approx 1.74 \times 10^{-16} )\).

  1. Constant variability of residuals
plot(abs(movmod$residuals) ~ movmod$fitted)

The absolute values of the residuals are distributed randomly.

  1. Independence of residuals
plot(movmod$residuals)

The residuals are scattered randomly. Therefore, we can conclude that there is no time series structure in the data i.e. the observations are independent of each other and the order of data collection does not have any impact on the model.

  1. Linearity between residuals and numerical variables
plot(movmod$residuals ~ mdata$runtime)

plot(movmod$residuals ~ mdata$critics_score)

The numerical variables are runtime and critics_score. With respect to both of them, the residuals are scattered randomsly around 0. Therefore, we can conclude that there is a linear relationship between the predicted value and these variables.

4.6 Interpretation

Interpretation of coefficients are presented here.

Parameter Interpretation
Intercept On average, the model predictst that the audience_score for a movie of genre “Action” with a runtime of 0 and critics_score of 0 would be 27.37.
Coefficient of runtime All else held constant, on average, a unit increase of run-time would increase the audience_score by about 0.075.
Coefficient of critics_score All else held constant, on average, a unit increase of critics_score would increase the audience_score by about 0.45.
Levels of genre with +ve coefficients All else held constant, on average, a movie with either of the genres “Art house”, “Musical”, “Animation”, “Documentary”, “Drama”, “Other” would have a higher audience_score with a relevant value of 5.74, 9.78, 5.94, 9.45, 1.68, or 1.80, respectively.
Levels of genre with -ve coefficients All else held constant, on average, a movie with either of the genres “Mystery”, “Sci-Fi”, “Comedy”, “Horror” would have a lower audience_score with a corresponding value of -4.39, -6.54, -0.54, or -8.22 respectively.
Adjusted \(R^2\) 52.35 % of the variability of audience_score can be explained by the model.

5. Prediction

The chosen movies from the year 2016 is “Nerve”. The data came from the link: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/nerve_2016. The details are as follows.

Parameter Value
Audience score 66%
Run-time 96 minutes
Critical Score 66%
Genre Action

Let us create a data frame for this data.

nerve <- data.frame(runtime = 96, critics_score = 66, genre = "Action")

Prediction for the movie.

predict(movmod, nerve)
##        1 
## 64.25884

Interpretation of the prediction: The model predicts, on average, a movie with 66% critical score, of “Action” genre, with a run-time of 96 minutes would have an audience score of 64.26%. This values is very close to the real value given in the above reference i.e. 66%.

The prediction interval for the movie at 95% confidence is given below.

predict(movmod, nerve, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr     upr
## 1 64.25884 36.59337 91.9243

Interpretation of the prediction interval: The model predicts, on average, with a 95% confidence, that an “Action” movie of run-time of 96 minutes having a critical score of 66% would have an audience score between 36.59% and 91.92%. The real value (66%) is encapsulated by the predicted interval i.e. the prediction and the real value agree with the interval.

6. Conclusion

Based on the diagnostics, the model is very suitable for the task. The value of the audience_score is strongly associated with the variables runtime, genre, and critics_score. The model provides agreeable predictions based on its training data set. In the test case, the deviation between the real value and the prediction was about 2%.

Shortcomings:
One of the issues with this type of analysis is that most movies belong to multiple genres. For instance, the movie “Nerve” also belongs to the Mystery genre according to the source. In such cases, the audience score might be erroneous because different people watch different movies based on their personal preferences and this might impact the score they would attach to the movie.

Another important fact is that the training data set (provided in “movies.RData”) might not be a representative set. For example, there are more “Feature films” than documentaries etc. The same is true for other title types and genres. This could, in theory, give rise to a biased model.

Suggestions:
Use a larger, fairer sample from all the movies created in the Hollywood for developing a better model.
